<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-168-260  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 168 260.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  March 27 1989 v10 n13 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan software industry may challenge U.S. leadership.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>'Japanese Software, the Next Competitive Challenge', a report fromAdapso detailing the Japanese computer software industry, isdiscussed.andP;  Japan Information Service Industry Assn (JISIA)estimated the Japanese software market at $5.4 billion in 1986,and projects it will reach $33.1 billion by 2000.andP;  Most Japanesesoftware firms are affiliated with large computer manufacturers,and the independent software industry in Japan is acutelyunderdeveloped.andP;  The lavish use of software engineers to meetoverwhelming domestic demand for custom software, together withthe fact that software development is considered less prestigiousthan the hardware field, has created an acute shortage of softwareengineers in Japan.andP;  Intense efforts underway in Japan to dealwith software industry shortcomings should be a matter of concernfor the US industry.andP;  The TRON effort in Japan could result in anoperating system entirely developed in that country, and couldmake US penetration of Japanese computer and software markets moredifficult.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanSoftwareIndustry AnalysisTrendsJapanese Competition.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Growth rate of the Japanese software industry. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>